he West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman: of uncertain origin. Tengvik suggests derivation from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Skrópi</i> (of doubtful etymology, but compare Old Scandinavian  <i>skrópa-maðr</i> ‘hypocrite’, containing the genitive plural form of  <i>skrópar</i> ‘sham, hypocrisy’). It is possible, but not certain, that this personal name forms the first element of the Notts place-name Scrooby. Otherwise there is no evidence for its currency in England or, more relevantly, in Normandy. Richards Castle (in Herefs and Shrops) was apparently named after Richard Scrope, who held estates in Herefs and Worcs in 1066 and was a Norman favourite of Edward the Confessor. The Scrope family, whose name is traditionally pronounced /skru:p/, was politically important in medieval England, and acquired estates in Lincs (Barton on Humber), NR Yorks (Castle Bolton), and in ER Yorks (Flotmanby). Richard (le) Scrope of Bolton, in Wensleydale, was Lord Chancellor in the reign of Richard II. The use of  <i>le</i> and  <i>de</i> in the surname, suggesting either a nickname or a locative name, must be treated with caution because these were often added gratuitously to Anglo-Norman surnames as a sign of high social status."],"variants":[{"name":"Scroop","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]},{"name":"Scroope","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Simon Scrope was born in 1162 as the son of Sir Robert Le Scrope. He married Imgoline Chaworth in 1182, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died after March 1206, and was buried in Wensley, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1162–Aft March 1206":"1162–pärast märtsi 1206","1162–1206":"1162–1206","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1173–1205":"1173–1205","–1220":"–1220","1164–1246":"1164–1246","1183–1224":"1183–1224","1188–Female":"1188–Surnud","1134–1198":"1134–1198","about 1183":"umbes 1183","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1162":"1162","1173":"1173","1183":"1183","1182":"1182","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","Aft March 1206":"pärast märtsi 1206","1134":"1134","1188":"1188","after 1198":"pärast 1198","about 1188":"umbes 1188","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Flotmanby,   Yorkshire, England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wensley, Yorkshire, England":"Wensley, Yorkshire, England","Millington, Yorkshire, England":"Millington, Yorkshire, England","Wensley, North Yorkshire, England, UK":"Wensley, North Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1162–Aft March 1206":"1162–maaliskuu 1206 jälkeen","1162–1206":"1162–1206","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1173–1205":"1173–1205","–1220":"–1220","1164–1246":"1164–1246","1183–1224":"1183–1224","1188–Female":"1188–Kuollut","1134–1198":"1134–1198","about 1183":"noin 1183","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1162":"1162","1173":"1173","1183":"1183","1182":"1182","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","Aft March 1206":"maaliskuu 1206 jälkeen","1134":"1134","1188":"1188","after 1198":"1198 jälkeen","about 1188":"noin 1188","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, En